  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Defends extended functionalism against objections, particularly the concern that functional criteria are too permissive and would count too many things as cognitive. Proposes additional constraints on extended cognition including portability, reliability, and automatic endorsement, while maintaining that functional role rather than intrinsic properties determines cognitive status. The coupling-constitution distinction is not metaphysically fundamental but reflects different ways of individuating functional systems.

  RELEVANCE: Addresses the key worry that functionalist defenses of extended cognition are too liberal. Shows how functional criteria can be refined without collapsing back into internalism. Important for understanding how defenders of extended cognition can acknowledge constraints on cognitive extension while rejecting the coupling-constitution distinction as Adams and Aizawa formulate it.

